\begin_layout Section
Data matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data Matrices provide values for a number of items (i.e.
 genes) in several conditions.
 Data Matrices can provide continuous values (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

) or binary values (1, 0).
 Any continuous Data Matrix can be converted to a binary Data Matrix in
 GiTools providing a criteria (i.e.
 value higher than 2).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Modules are lists of genes or other items with a common biological property.
 For example, genes in the same pathway form a module.
 They are also called gene sets or concepts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Tables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Annotations are files that provide mappings to synonymous ids, descriptions
 or any other information about the items used in the analysis.
 Annotations can refer to Columns or Rows in any Data matrix or Result matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
How can I get them ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can import Data Matrices directly from Biomart or IntOGen or prepare
 them in an excel file and save the file as tab separated file.
 If you import matrices and modules from IntOGen the annotation files are
 already provided by default.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
File formats
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Continuous Data Matrices are provided in CDM format while Binary Data Matrices
 can be provided in sevaral formats depending on what is more convenient
 to the user.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Continuous data matrix (CDM)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CDM file format is a tab delimited matrix of items (i.e.
 genes) and conditions.
 The numbers in each cell indicates the values that this item has in that
 condition.
\end_layout

